HEADWORD: Alterative
<hw>Al"ter*a*tive</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>alterativus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>alt⟦eacute⟧ratif</ets>.]</ety>
<def>Causing ateration.</def> <specif>Specifically:</specif>
<def>Gradually changing, or tending to change, a morbid state of the
functions into one of health.</def> <rj><au>Burton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Alterative</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Alterative
<hw>Al"ter*a*tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A medicine or treatment which
gradually induces a change, and restores healthy functions without
sensible evacuations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Altercate</ent>⟦br⟧
